1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,705
In this video, we're going to look at both absolute and relative frequency plots.

2
00:00:06,705 --> 00:00:12,720
We're going to start by importing the necessary libraries, numpy, pandas,

3
00:00:12,720 --> 00:00:19,200
matplotlib, and Seaborn, and also read in our dataset, the diamonds dataset.

4
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:21,840
Now, if we're interested in plotting

5
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:27,420
absolute values or the total number of counts for a variable,

6
00:00:27,420 --> 00:00:31,170
we can use a count plot, for instance,

7
00:00:31,170 --> 00:00:34,520
we can use value counts to look at

8
00:00:34,520 --> 00:00:39,370
the total number of counts for each diamond clarity grade.

9
00:00:39,370 --> 00:00:46,000
We can use value counts to get the order in decreasing prevalence.

10
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:53,060
We can use a count plot to make a vertical or horizontal absolute frequency plot.

11
00:00:53,060 --> 00:00:57,505
Here we're using a horizontal frequency plot.

12
00:00:57,505 --> 00:01:00,530
However, if we want to answer the question,

13
00:01:00,530 --> 00:01:05,105
what percentage of diamonds are internally flawless?

14
00:01:05,105 --> 00:01:06,860
That's the IF grade.

15
00:01:06,860 --> 00:01:11,180
Well, here would have to do some mental math and estimate.

16
00:01:11,180 --> 00:01:16,375
Now instead, we could create a relative frequency plot.

17
00:01:16,375 --> 00:01:20,260
In order to do that, we can't use a count plot,

18
00:01:20,260 --> 00:01:26,170
because a count plot requires integer values and we're looking to plot a proportion,

19
00:01:26,170 --> 00:01:29,200
so instead we must use a bar plot.

20
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:32,650
The first thing we need to do is normalize the data.

21
00:01:32,650 --> 00:01:34,585
There are two ways to do this.

22
00:01:34,585 --> 00:01:38,200
We can still use value counts, except instead,

23
00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:42,150
we can just pass in normalize equals true.

24
00:01:42,150 --> 00:01:47,470
This will provide the normalized values where the total number of

25
00:01:47,470 --> 00:01:53,110
counts for each type is divided by the total number of counts in the dataset.

26
00:01:53,110 --> 00:01:58,810
Then we can convert this series into a full DataFrame,

27
00:01:58,810 --> 00:02:01,505
which is what we're doing right here.

28
00:02:01,505 --> 00:02:06,700
Then we can pass this into the bar plot, just like before.

29
00:02:06,700 --> 00:02:10,090
Now we see the total number of diamonds that are internally

30
00:02:10,090 --> 00:02:14,255
flawless is around 3 and a 1/2 or 4%.

31
00:02:14,255 --> 00:02:18,985
The SI1, which is the most frequent grade,

32
00:02:18,985 --> 00:02:21,395
is almost a quarter of the data.

33
00:02:21,395 --> 00:02:24,985
Alternatively, maybe we could combine

34
00:02:24,985 --> 00:02:28,870
an absolute frequency plot with a relative frequency plot.

35
00:02:28,870 --> 00:02:33,085
This is where matplotlib shines,

36
00:02:33,085 --> 00:02:35,330
because it is so flexible.

37
00:02:35,330 --> 00:02:41,635
Here what we're going to do is we're going to go back to using a count plot,

38
00:02:41,635 --> 00:02:46,250
except we are then going to iterate over

39
00:02:46,250 --> 00:02:51,500
each bar and then we're going to convert it into a percentage.

40
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:58,400
What we're going to end up doing is creating a string where we look at

41
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:02,870
the count of that quality grade divided by

42
00:03:02,870 --> 00:03:08,530
the total number of counts in the entire dataset.

43
00:03:08,530 --> 00:03:13,130
Here we see that now we have both access to

44
00:03:13,130 --> 00:03:15,140
the absolute number of

45
00:03:15,140 --> 00:03:19,710
each clarity grade in our dataset as well as the relative proportion.

